  <tr>
   <td colspan="4" class="content">
    <pre>(Relevant wiki page, for the record: <a href="https://openhatch.org/wiki/Account_deletion">https://openhatch.org/wiki/Account_deletion</a>)

What if when a user wants to delete their account, they click a "delete me" button that does all the 
easily-automated deletion tasks, and it also automatically sends an email to <a href="mailto:hello@openhatch.org">hello@openhatch.org</a> 
requesting that admins do the remaining manual steps if necessary?

That seems more convenient for the user.</pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
 
  <tr>
   <th><a href="msg3849">msg3849 (view)</a></th>
   <th>Author: paulproteus</th>
   <th>Date: 2013-09-11.23:10:25</th>
   <th>
    
   </th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td colspan="4" class="content">
    <pre>For MediaWiki, we can "delete" users (britta-style delete) if we add this 
extension: <a href="http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Extension:User_Merge_and_Delete">http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Extension:User_Merge_and_Delete</a> . It 
requires being an admin.

For Vanilla: We can delete users there, too, via the web UI (also by my admin 
spam-removal scripts, but I figure that tool shouldn't have these two very 
different purposes).

If we can automate both of those, then have that be executed by the oh-mainline 
code for when you are deleted, that is excellent. But if not, I propose: we 
should just write a wiki page for admins indicating how to use the above tools, 
and then when a user gets deleted, email <a href="mailto:hello@openhatch.org">hello@openhatch.org</a> indicating which 
user to do the processing on.

Thoughts?</pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
 
  <tr>
   <th><a href="msg3797">msg3797 (view)</a></th>
   <th>Author: brittag</th>
   <th>Date: 2013-08-08.00:48:38</th>
   <th>
    
   </th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td colspan="4" class="content">
    <pre>What does it mean for a Roundup user or wiki user to be deleted, since their contributions can't 
really be deleted (I think?)? What about an associated Vanilla forum user?

I imagine that a user-who-wants-to-be-deleted is mainly interested in making their 
name/username and any other personal information get removed from OpenHatch stuff, and 
making their account inactive/invisible (and unable to be logged into).

If that's a good guess, maybe that could be accomplished by renaming/anonymizing the accounts 
that can't really be practically deleted, and deleting any personal details associated with those 
accounts? Including deleting their user page &amp; user talk page on the wiki, and maybe removing their 
username from wiki talk pages where they signed their name (if any)?</pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
 
  <tr>
   <th><a href="msg3742">msg3742 (view)</a></th>
   <th>Author: paulproteus</th>
   <th>Date: 2013-07-22.19:15:54</th>
   <th>
    
   </th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td colspan="4" class="content">
    <pre>I think this should work something like email confirmation works generally, 
where you get sent an email to confirm your deletion, and then we delete you.

Note that in theory this is tricky; when the main OH user goes away, should the 
Roundup user and wiki users get deleted as well?

We should decide that.</pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
